  "kreditpunkte": 4,
  "lernziele": "<p>Digital Signal Processing 1 and Digital Signal Processing 2 form together a one-year introductory sequence into modern digital signal processing</p>",
  "vorausgKenntnisse": "<ul><li>Fundamental knowledge of calculus</li><li>Fundamental knowledge of Fourier analysis</li><li>Fundamental knowledge of probability theory</li><li>Fundamental knowledge of linear algebra</li><li>Solid command of the English language, since the lectures are in English</li></ul>",
  "semesterBewertung": "keine Note oder Wertung",
  "sprache": "de-CH",
  "zustand": "aktiviert",
  "kurse": [
    {
      "id": 28178,
      "kuerzel": "DigSig1Engl",
      "bezeichnung": "Digital Signal Processing 1",
      "lernziele": "<p>At the end of the module the students are expected to understand the following concepts and be able to apply them to real world signal processing problems:</p><ul><li>Sampling and Reconstruction</li><li>Quantization</li><li>Discrete-Time Systems</li><li>FIR Filtering and Convolution</li><li>z-Transform</li><li>Transfer Functions</li></ul>",
      "planinhalt": "<p>The module is structured as follows:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Sampling and Reconstruction</li>\n<li>Quantization</li>\n<li>Discrete-Time Systems</li>\n<li>FIR Filtering and Convolution</li>\n<li>z-Transform</li>\n<li>Transfer Functions</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The lecture is based on the excellent and freely available book \"Introduction to Signal Processing\" by Sophocles J. Orfanidis. This book also has a useful website: http://eceweb1.rutgers.edu/~orfanidi/intro2sp/</p>",
